faster way to train and test your models in R¶

NOTE: since you were given only half of the data during the session you do not need to do the following. You should use your data as training data and the new data as test data. However, if you have followed the steps above and loaded the dataset from the MASS library, go on and execude the code below:¶

Train and Test data¶

lets split the data into train and test data (that's what caTools libarry is for)¶

In [104]:
#set a seed 
set.seed(123)

#Split the data , `split()` assigns a booleans to a new column based on the SplitRatio specified. 

split = sample.split(BostonHousing,SplitRatio =0.75)


train = subset(BostonHousing,split==TRUE)
test = subset(BostonHousing,split==FALSE)

# now we are using 75% of the data for training or model and 25% for testing our model

let's build our model using the variables that have a medium to high correlation with medv¶

  • crim
  • indus
  • nox
  • rm
  • tax
  • ptratio
  • lstat
In [105]:
model_1 = lm(medv ~ crim + indus + nox + rm + tax + ptratio + lstat, data=train)

Prediction!¶

In [118]:
test$predicted.medv = predict(model_2,test)
library(dplyr) #the piping

pl_model2 <-test %>% 
  ggplot(aes(medv,predicted.medv)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) + 
  stat_smooth(aes(colour='black')) +
  xlab('Actual value of medv') +
  ylab('Predicted value of medv')+
  theme_bw()

#ggplotly(pl1)  I am using jupyter so interactive graphs are not supported
plot(pl_model2)

Interaction terms¶

how to choose interaction terms. go back to the correlation plot at the beginning of the notebook. we can see that rm and lstat are highly correlated. since both of these variables are included in our model, let's make them interactive¶

In [123]:
model_interact = lm(medv ~  rm * lstat +  ptratio, data=train)
test$predicted.medv = predict(model_interact,test)


pl_interact <-test %>% 
  ggplot(aes(medv,predicted.medv)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) + 
  stat_smooth(aes(colour='black')) +
  xlab('Actual value of medv') +
  ylab('Predicted value of medv')+
  theme_bw()

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
#ggplotly(pl1)  I am using jupyter so interactive graphs are not supported
plot(pl_model2)
plot(pl_interact)

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
